{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528993","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528993"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:49:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:49:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14351"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14351"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.01,0.05,0.12,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7046"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110297"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7046"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92568"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"4478"},{"type":"tags","id":"4479"},{"type":"tags","id":"8045"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12806"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41216"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110297"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the labour ward in active labour at 39 weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and has had an uncomplicated pregnancy. She does not take any regular medications. After a six-hour labour, she gives birth to a baby boy. The midwife performs an assessment of the newborn.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the baby has good tone and is moving all limbs. His heart rate is 130 beats per minute. He has a strong cry and is breathing well. His entire body is pink except for his hands and feet, which are slightly blue.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the Apgar score at one minute after birth?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["9","3","10","7","5"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Apgar score is a rapid assessment of a newborn\u0027s condition performed at one and five minutes after birth. It evaluates five criteria: Appearance (colour), Pulse (heart rate), Grimace (reflex irritability), Activity (muscle tone), and Respiration. Each criterion is scored 0, 1, or 2, with a maximum total score of 10.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, let\u0027s break down the Apgar score based on the information provided:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E9\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct Apgar score for this newborn at one minute after birth. Here\u0027s how we arrive at this score:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Appearance (colour): The baby\u0027s body is pink except for blue extremities, which is normal for a newborn. Score: 1\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Pulse (heart rate): The heart rate is 130 beats per minute, which is above 100. Score: 2\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Grimace (reflex irritability): The stem doesn\u0027t explicitly mention this, but a strong cry suggests good reflex irritability. Score: 2\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Activity (muscle tone): The baby has good tone and is moving all limbs. Score: 2\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E- Respiration: The baby is breathing well with a strong cry. Score: 2\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal score: 1 + 2 + 2 + 2 + 2 = 9\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E10\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate a perfect score, which is rare immediately after birth. Most newborns score 1 for appearance due to blue extremities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E7\u003C/strong\u003E is still considered a normal Apgar score but is lower than what this baby\u0027s condition suggests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E5\u003C/strong\u003E indicates moderate difficulty and would not be consistent with the described vigorous newborn.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E3\u003C/strong\u003E is a critically low score suggesting significant distress, which doesn\u0027t match this baby\u0027s condition at all.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that while the Apgar score is a useful tool for assessing a newborn\u0027s immediate condition, it is not used to predict long-term health outcomes. A score of 7-10 is considered normal, 4-6 is moderately abnormal, and 0-3 is critically low. The five-minute Apgar score is generally more indicative of the newborn\u0027s overall condition than the one-minute score.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Apgar score is assessed at one and five minutes after birth to evaluate a newborn\u0027s condition.","A score of 7-10 is considered normal, 4-6 moderately abnormal, and 0-3 critically low.","The Apgar score includes assessment of appearance, pulse, grimace, activity, and respiration."],"references":["Simon LV, Shah M, Bragg BN. APGAR Score. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 [updated 2024 Mar 19]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470569/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92568"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14351"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92568"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T15:29:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T15:29:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"704